light, constant, not stubborne. Bee liberall to all men, fawning on no man: familiar with fewe, and upright to everie one. Beleeve not lightly e verie rumour, accusation, or concei ved suspicion. Despise vaine glorie, and bee no sharpe exactour of the goods that thou hast. Use fewe wordes thy selfe, but suffer them that speake. Bee grave, not rough, nor contemning the merrie nature. Bee desirous and appliable to bee taught wisedome, imparte what thou kno west to him taht demaundeth without anie arrogancie, and desire to learne the things that thou knowest not, without hiding thine ignoraunce. A wise man will not chaunge his common countrie fashion, not make the people gaze on him with newe found devises. Thus much have I hitherto recited touching continencie, out of the writings of the blessed Bi shoppe Martine of Dumia. Wee for our partes must pray to the Lorde, that hee will vouchsafe to bestow on us his holie spirite, by which the force of continencie in all things may take roote in our hearts, to the bringing foorth of fruite in our deedes, agreea ble to the prescript rule of this com maunded continencie. For unlesse the holy ghost doe quicken and inspire us, we doe in vaine give eare to so many and so good commaundements, and unlesse we live and leade a temperate and a sober live, wee are utterly un worthie to beare the name of Chri stians. To this place also doth the treatise of fasting belong, which I meane to handle in as fewe wordes, as conve niently can be: Christian fasting is a discipline, ordering and chastening of the bodie for the present necessitie, which wee beginne and keepe of our
owne accord without compulsion, and
wherewith we humble our selfes in
the fight of God, by drawing from the
bodie the matter that setteth the sieth
on fire, therby to make it obey the spi
rite. For so long as we mortall men
do live in this bodie, the flesh doth still
resist the spirite, and most of all rebel
leth then, when we with delicates doe
pamper the bodie. Wherefore fasting
doth draw from the bodie everie evil.
which stirreth up and strengtheneth it
against the good commaundements of
Gods holie spirite.
Now the necessitie, for which wee
keepe this fasting, is of two fortes,
publique and private. Wee fast for
the publique or common necessitie,
when some calamitie doeth either op
presse or else hang over the head of
the Church. Oh such a manner of fa
sting we see examples in the 2 chap. of
Joel, and in the 3. of Jonas his prophe
cie: which verie same order in fasting
was used in the time of our Lord A
postles: as it is evidently extant in the
Acts of the Apostle. And this kinde
of fasting doth seeme to have differed
verie little among them of olde, from
a generall mourning: yea it seemeth
altogether to have beene nothing else,
but a kind of lamenting. In the scrip
tures every booke is full of examples,
which teach and instruct as howe the
holy Saints did humble themselves in
the fight of God with true repentance
for their sinnes and offences. Private
necessitie is that for which everie par
ticular man doth fast when hee feeleth
himselfe to be vexed with bodily con
cupiscence, that thereby hee may take
from the flesh the flame and fewell,
least the body at last be fixed and bur
ned. For the Lord in the Gospel saide,
that the children of the bride chamber
do fast when the bridegroome is taken
